        "excerpt": "You turn man back into dust and say, \"Return, O children of men.\" For a thousand years in Your sight are like yesterday when it passes by, or as a watch in the night.",
        "body": "Verse 3 is the chasm. The same God who exists from everlasting to everlasting *turns man back into dust*. The verb is sovereign — God acts, and the action is reversion. The vocabulary recalls Genesis 3:19 directly: *dust you are, and to dust you shall return*. Moses, the very author of Genesis on most evangelical readings, deliberately echoes the curse of Eden. Death is not a natural feature of being human; it is the consequence of the fall, and God Himself is the agent of return.\n\nVerse 4 sharpens the chasm with a comparative. A *thousand years in Your sight are like yesterday when it passes by, or as a watch in the night*. The Roman watch (*ashmurah*) was three to four hours — one shift of military duty. Moses piles two compressions: a millennium is yesterday (one rotation of earth) AND a watch in the night (one-eighth of that rotation). The reckoning is utterly other. This verse is cited verbatim in 2 Peter 3:8 to answer scoffers who say Christ delays His return — God's clock and ours do not run on the same calibration.\n\nVerses 5-6 collapse the metaphor onto a single morning. God *sweeps* generations away *like a flood* — the verb *zaram* is a flash-flood verb, used of torrents that scour the wadi. People *fall asleep* in death (Hebrew euphemism for dying). And then the central simile: humanity is *like grass*. In the morning it sprouts; toward evening it fades and withers. The desert grass Moses watched daily is the metaphor — explosive growth after rare rainfall, complete withering within hours of the scorching sun. The same image runs through Isaiah 40:6-8 and is taken up by Peter (1 Peter 1:24) and James (James 1:10-11). Three different biblical writers reach for the same Mosaic image to describe human life.\n\nThe morning-evening compression is theologically loaded. An entire human life, however long it feels from the inside, fits inside a single day in God's reckoning. The mountains are old; the people who climb them are grass. The God who watches all of human history is watching one withering afternoon.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Dakka* (dust, v.3) — literally *that which is crushed*, pulverized matter; stronger than the *aphar* of Genesis 3:19. *Zaram* (sweep away, v.5) — to flood, pour torrentially; the wadi-flood verb. *Chatsir* (grass, v.5) — the short-lived steppe grass of the wilderness, not pasture grass. *Yavesh* (withers, v.6) — to dry up, parch."
