        "number": 4,
        "title": "The pivot — teach us to number our days",
        "range": "90:12",
        "excerpt": "So teach us to number our days, that we may present to You a heart of wisdom.",
        "body": "Verse 12 is the axis on which the whole psalm turns. The Hebrew opens with *ken* — *so, thus, accordingly* — explicitly grounding the petition in everything that has come before. **Because** God is eternal (vv.1-2), **because** we are dust and grass (vv.3-6), **because** our days end under His wrath at our sin (vv.7-11), *therefore* — teach us to number our days. The wisdom-petition is not free-floating spirituality; it rests on the previous eleven verses.\n\nThe verb *teach* is the causative of *yada* — *make us know*. The same root as v.11's *who understands?* (*yada*). The rhetorical question of v.11 receives its only possible answer as a prayer in v.12: only the one whom God Himself causes to know will know. Natural humanity will not number its days. It will distract, accumulate, perform busyness, postpone, deny, anything but count. The unaided heart treats death as an interruption; the taught heart treats death as a horizon that re-prioritizes every choice this side of it.\n\n*Number our days* (*manah yameinu*) is the heart of the petition. The verb *manah* is the same verb used of counting an army (Numbers 1:3) or the stars (Psalm 147:4) — exact enumeration, not vague awareness. Moses does not ask God to teach Israel to *think about* death; he asks for the days themselves to be counted. The unnumbered day disappears into a fog of indistinct duration; the numbered day stands forward as a finite, given, accountable thing. Spurgeon: \"He who has not learned to number his days has not learned to live them.\"\n\nThe purpose of the numbering is *a heart of wisdom* (*levav chokhmah*). *Chokhmah* in OT wisdom literature is not theoretical knowledge but practical skill in living rightly under God — the same word used of the skilled craftsmen who built the tabernacle (Exodus 31:3, 6). Moses asks that the brief life become a workshop of righteous skill. The heart shaped by numbered days is the only heart that becomes wise; every other heart becomes merely clever, accomplished, or numb.\n\nThis is also the verse that exposes the difference between biblical wisdom and the Stoic *memento mori*. The Stoic numbers his days to achieve equanimity in the face of an indifferent universe. The Israelite numbers his days to receive *hesed* from a covenant God whose wrath is real and whose mercy is realer (vv.13-17). The numbering produces wisdom *because* it leads to prayer — not because counting itself is virtue.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ken* (so, v.12) — the strong inferential particle binding the petition to the previous eleven verses. *Manah* (number) — to count exactly, enumerate. *Levav* (heart) — the inner person, the seat of will, mind, and affection; not merely emotion. *Chokhmah* (wisdom) — applied skill in living, the same root used of tabernacle craftsmen."
