        "title": "Return, satisfy, gladden, establish — the fourfold petition",
        "range": "90:13-17",
        "excerpt": "Do return, O Lord; how long will it be? And be sorry for Your servants. O satisfy us in the morning with Your lovingkindness, that we may sing for joy and be glad all our days.",
        "body": "The final movement is petition — four imperatives that turn the meditation into urgent prayer. Each imperative reverses something from the indictment section.\n\n*Do return, O LORD; how long?* (v.13) — the verb *shuvah* reverses the wrath-distance implied in vv.7-11. *How long?* (*ad matai*) is the lament-formula used across the Psalter and Habakkuk; it does not impugn God's character but presses His promised mercy against present affliction. *Be sorry for Your servants* — the verb *nacham* is the same verb used in Exodus 32:14, where God *relented* concerning the harm He had spoken against Israel after Moses' intercession. Moses here prays Exodus 32 again, claiming the same covenant ground.\n\n*Satisfy us in the morning with Your lovingkindness* (v.14) — the morning that produced withering grass in vv.5-6 now becomes the time of *hesed*. The same *boqer*, opposite content. *Hesed* is the great covenant word — steadfast, loyal, faithful love that keeps promises made to the unworthy. The verb *sava* (satisfy) is the satiation language used of feasting (Psalm 22:26; 63:5). Moses asks God to *fill* the brief days with covenant love rather than wrath, so that the years that ended *like a sigh* (v.9) become years of *singing for joy and being glad all our days*.\n\n*Make us glad according to the days You have afflicted us, and the years we have seen evil* (v.15) — the petition for *symmetry*. Moses asks God for joy proportionate to past grief, gladness measured by the same yardstick as affliction. This is one of the boldest prayers in the Psalter; it asks God to make the recompense match the suffering. The New Testament picks up the principle in 2 Corinthians 4:17 (the affliction works an eternal weight of glory) and Romans 8:18 (sufferings not worth comparing with glory). Moses is asking inside the wilderness for what will only be answered fully on the other side of the resurrection.\n\n*Let Your work appear to Your servants and Your majesty to their children* (v.16) — the petition for visibility. Moses asks that God's *poal* (deeds, acts) actually become visible in this generation and the next. The wilderness generation died largely without seeing the work; the petition asks that the children at least see what the parents did not.\n\n*Let the favor of the Lord our God be upon us; and confirm for us the work of our hands; yes, confirm the work of our hands* (v.17) — the closing imperative, doubled for emphasis. *Noam* (favor, beauty, pleasantness) is the gracious countenance of God resting on the community. And the doubled *kun* (confirm, establish, make firm) is the answer to everything verses 3-10 have said about transience. Grass withers; lives end like sighs; mountains were born and will perish. But God can *establish* — give permanence to — the work of mortal hands. The doubled imperative is emphatic Hebrew rhetoric; what is doubled is what is most urgently desired. The brief life prays not merely to be saved from wrath but to be made *productive*, with fruit that lasts. Paul's *your labor is not in vain in the Lord* (1 Corinthians 15:58) is the resurrection answer to Moses' wilderness petition.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shuvah* (return, v.13) — repent, turn back; here imperative aimed at God to reverse His judgment. *Nacham* — to relent, be moved to compassion; the Exodus 32:14 verb. *Sava* (satisfy, v.14) — to be filled to satiety. *Hesed* — covenant loyalty, faithful love. *Noam* (v.17) — the beautiful favor of God's countenance. *Kun* (establish, v.17) — to make firm, fix in place; the verb used of God's establishing of David's throne (2 Samuel 7:12), here applied to the brief work of human hands."
